From a version controlled package, it is possible to access updates from the current SVN tag using
Package Control/File History
this will retrieve the list of updates from the SVN repository, choose the top version and then use the "Retrieve" button.
Unfortunately there seems to be no simple way of doing this with a shortcut from the top level.
If a package undergoes a major change, that may invalidate dependent usage, this will be deployed as a new release. (See "Getting a new release of a package")

Creating a local copy to hack can be done two ways:
1) turn off version control on package, export to new location, reload from this location
or
2) Follow the "Create a new release" procedure, but place the new version under "branches" instead of "tags"
The second approach allows you to share hacked versions without making changes to the source release or consensus position on the trunk.
